Like almost everything between the starting exposition and the end results of the movie was Raimi, and the rest was Marvel. But the Marvel part felt like it was not consequential at all, just fan-service with no intentional storytelling.

@therealsupes 1. Infinity War 
2. Multiverse of madness 
3. No way home 
4. GOTG 2 
5. Iron man 
6. Winter soldier 
7. GOTG 
8. Civil War 
9. Avengers 
10. Homecoming

Case in point, No Way Home. Loved the Fan Service (<3 Alfred Molina). But I felt tired by the end of the movie. The resolution was just a flashy way of saying "everything this movie did don't matter lol".
And everything Doctor Strange did in this movie don't matter either. Just a bunch of references that reminded me how old I am, but not leading to anywhere.

Every Avenger movie before End Game was leading up to the big moment, and every fan-service was a promise of a new thread of story that would contribute to the ultimate team for the war. Now there is no enemy, no story thread leading anywhere. But fan-service keeps coming.

Maybe this is me venting up that I MAY not watch ALL Marvel movies anymore (probably will keep watching though). But new characters keep coming, and now it just looks like all the Multiverse stuff for this new Marvel phase doesn't mean much.

Ok, first let's get the positive out of the way:

doctor strange made me feel so many things lmfao

However that's where my main problem comes from it. The only way I could really put it is that MoM is a pretty good Marvel movie, but not so much a "movie" movie. It could be that I've been pampered with what phase 4 has been so far, but this was so newcomer unfriendly

The plot relied so much on prior knowledge, which I know is pretty much required for a sequel, but to be able to fully enjoy the movie, you legitimately needed to watch everything tied to it. I could attest for this considering I watched with people who weren't too big on Marvel-

-who was able to enjoy NWH without watching the Garfield / Tobey movies, yet was left a bit off with MoM

Tying MoM to D+ shows was something I was afraid of as obviously not everyone has access to D+, so they are missing out on the experience. Really hoping this isn't the trend

Despite this, I don't think it deserves the lower rating it got. There was so much creativity in the film and it genuinely looked so beautiful, and it's all thanks to Raimi + his crew.
